        "title": "ðŸ“š Theory: More on Tenses: The Habitual Tense",
        "content": {
          "introduction": "The most common way to form the habitual tense is using '-ga' after the verb.",
          "phrases": [
            {
                "dholuo": "Achiemoga",
                "english": "I usually eat",
                "notes": "The -ga suffix at the verb indicates that the verb is done habitually."
              },
              {
                "dholuo": "Achiewoga gokinyi", 
                "english": "I usually wake up in the morning",
                "notes": "Derived from the verb 'chiewo' which means 'to wake up'."
              },
              {
                "dholuo": "Aheroga kwon", 
                "english": "I usually like kwon",
                "notes": "Derived from the verb 'hero' which means 'to love'. Also, 'kwon' is the dholuo word for 'Ugali', the staple dish of Kenya."
              }
            ]
              }
        },
